  "text": "The effects of fish oil in early RA, in the context of a treat-to-target strategy of DMARDs combination, were explored in a RCT by Proudman SM and co-authors. All enrolled patients started a DMARDs combination therapy including methotrexate, sulfasalazine, hydroxychloroquine and then leflunomide, according to a predetermined algorithm. Every step in the algorithm was based on disease activity and safety issues. The primary outcome measure was failure of triple DMARDs therapy. Failure of triple DMARDs therapy was lower in the fish oil group (HR = 0.24). The rate of first American College of Rheumatology (ACR) remission was significantly greater in the fish oil group (HR = 2.09) [CITATION_1] . This is another pivotal study because is the first exploring the effect of fish oil supplementation in the frame of the current RA management. The study is optimally designed and the results are just impressive.",
